We have a bijection $f: A \to B$ with $f(a) = b$. 

To construct the bijection between $A \setminus \{a\}$ and $B \setminus \{b\}$:

- For $x \in A \setminus \{a\}$, we map to $f(x) \in B \setminus \{b\}$. This is well-defined because $f$ is injective on $A$ (so $f(x) \neq f(a) = b$ when $x \neq a$).
- For $y \in B \setminus \{b\}$, we map to some $x \in A \setminus \{a\}$ such that $f(x) = y$. This exists because $f$ is surjective from $A$ to $B$ (so there is some $x \in A$ with $f(x) = y$), and if $x = a$ then $f(a) = y$ which would mean $b = y$, contradicting $y \neq b$.

